04688nam a22005655i 9780822391470DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223914707 a10.1515/97808223914702doi  a(DE-B1597)553978  a(OCoLC)308677468  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aGV1196.4.S63bL48 2008 7aSPO0530002bisacsh04a796.8122221 aLevi, Heather, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe World of Lucha Libre :bSecrets, Revelations, and Mexican National Identity /cHeather Levi; Emily S. Rosenberg, Gilbert M. Joseph. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b18 b&w illustrations, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican encounters/global interactions00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue -- tCHAPTER 1 Staging Contradiction -- tCHAPTER 2 Trade Secrets and Revelations -- tCHAPTER 3 Of Charros and Jaguars: The Moral and Social Cosmos of Lucha Libre -- tCHAPTER 4 The Wrestling Mask -- tCHAPTER 5 A Struggle between Two Strong Men? -- tCHAPTER 6 Mediating the Mask: Lucha Libre and Circulation -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe World of Lucha Libre is an insider's account of lucha libre, the popular Mexican form of professional wrestling. Heather Levi spent more than a year immersed in the world of wrestling in Mexico City. Not only did she observe live events and interview wrestlers, referees, officials, promoters, and reporters; she also apprenticed with a retired luchador (wrestler). Drawing on her insider's perspective, she explores lucha libre as a cultural performance, an occupational subculture, and a set of symbols that circulate through Mexican culture and politics. Levi argues that the broad appeal of lucha libre lies in its capacity to stage contradictions at the heart of Mexican national identity: between the rural and the urban, tradition and modernity, ritual and parody, machismo and feminism, politics and spectacle.Levi considers lucha libre in light of scholarship about sport, modernization, and the formation of the Mexican nation-state, and in connection to professional wrestling in the United States. She examines the role of secrecy in wrestling, the relationship between wrestlers and the characters they embody, and the meanings of the masks worn by luchadors. She discusses male wrestlers who perform masculine roles, those who cross-dress and perform feminine roles, and female wrestlers who wrestle each other. Investigating the relationship between lucha libre and the mass media, she highlights the history of the sport's engagement with television: it was televised briefly in the early 1950s, but not again until 1991. Finally, Levi traces the circulation of lucha libre symbols in avant-garde artistic movements and its appropriation in left-wing political discourse. The World of Lucha Libre shows how a sport imported from the United States in the 1930s came to be an iconic symbol of Mexican cultural authenticity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aWrestlingxSocial aspectszMexico. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / Wrestling.2bisacsh1 aJoseph, Gilbert M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRosenberg, Emily S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822391470zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822391470423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822391470.jpg  a9